comments.body: I could not find any repositories on https://bitbucket.org/princeton/ which might hold this.
On the dataspace.princeton.edu server, subdirectories within `/dspace` do have the custom theme included within `/dspace/webapps/jspui/`, but this is *not* tracked within a git repository.

`/usr/local/DR/home/dspace/dspace.git` is a git repository, with commit logs indicating that this has been pushing to the remote for https://github.com/PrincetonUniversityLibrary/dspace. However, it also seems to be the case that this code base is shared for the OAR.

The JSP files are located within `/usr/local/DR/home/dspace/dspace.git/dspace-jspui/src/main/webapp`, where the theme has been implemented by overriding the JSPUI theme, and the files are tracked on the `dataspace` branch of the git repository.

research-data-harvester.title: Research and Document harvesting from OpenNeuro
Research and Document harvesting from NIMH Data Archive

comments.body:
Regarding the error I was getting from the swagger UI, here's the relevant Q/A (for posterity):

---
Hello,

Weâ€™re starting a project to harvest metadata about datasets from Princeton University researchers from different data repositories.

Iâ€™m looking at your API documentation and I hope you can help me with some questions.

First, is the search API the best way to harvest metadata? I.e. do you offer any other harvesting services or endpoints such as OAI-PMH?

Second, the documentation [1] states that the search api does not require authentication. But when I try it out on the swagger ui [2] it returns a 401 Unauthorized code [3]. Do I actually need authentication or is there a bug with the swagger ui?

Finally, in the UI when I go to â€œGet Dataâ€ > â€œData from Labsâ€ I can select â€œPrinceton Universityâ€ in the â€œOrganizationâ€ field to get the results Iâ€™m interested in. How can I replicate that search with the API? Iâ€™m not sure what querystring parameters to use since they donâ€™t appear in my url when I submit the form.

Thanks so much for your help,
Anna

[1] https://nda.nih.gov/tools/apis.html
[2] https://nda.nih.gov/api/search/docs/swagger-ui.html#!/search/searchUsingPOST_1
[3]
```
 {
"timestamp": 1589995033017,
"status": 401,
"error": "Unauthorized",
"message": "Full authentication is required to access this resource",
"path": "/api/search/api/search/nda/%7Btypes%7D/full"
}
```

---
Hello Anna,

There is an error in the swagger user interface configuration, it currently has a property set for base url of 
[ base url: /api/search/api/search ]

The API does have protected non-public endpoints, and the configuration requires authentication for any requests that aren't for public-facing endpoints whether they are exist or not. That is reason you are getting the 401 unauthorized response.

...(the rest of the response is in the comment above)
I'll update this if I get any more info from them, but I'm going to go ahead and close.

research-data-harvester.title: Produce initial list of fields we hope to collect

comments.body:
@windcowles I included both dates because imagined scenarios like:

* Dataset creation and deposit were separated by a large span of time (e.g. it sat around on a hard drive for 15 years and then was deposited, long after the related paper was published)
* Dataset was created / deposited, then reviewed and corrected or updated at a later time and then deposited again.

For now I'll change it to just say "date". This may be more realistically what we end up with, assuming there's variation on what repositories provide.

research-data-harvester.title: Research and document harvesting data from Zenodo

comments.body:
I asked about having a set created for us to use with their OAI-PMH service.

Response:
"We usually create new custom harvesting sets for record queries that can be easily filtered in terms of their metadata fields and receive often updates. Since we don't have in our metadata an easy machine-readable way for specifying author affiliation, it would be also difficult to define a set based on a generic search query."

They advised us to use the REST API; documenting that on the wiki.
